    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and it mentioned lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles when u go hard and how the body gets rid of it afterwards?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! When you engage in high-intensity interval training (HIIT), your muscles are working at a high rate, producing a lot of energy. This energy production involves a process called anaerobic glycolysis, which breaks down glucose for energy without using oxygen. As a result, lactic acid is produced as a byproduct. The body then converts it into lactate, which can be transported in the bloodstream to the liver, where it can be converted back into glucose or metabolized for energy. This process helps to clear the lactic acid from your muscles and maintain energy levels during intense workouts.",
